'''Tanitoluwa Oluwatimilehin Oluwaseyi''' (born May 15, 2000) is a professional [[Association football|soccer]] player who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for {{Spanish football updater|Villarreal}} club [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]]. Born in Nigeria, he represents the [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada national team]].

==Early life==
Oluwaseyi was born in [[Abuja]], Nigeria, but moved to [[Mississauga]], Canada at age 10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlsnextpro.com/news/black-voices-in-soccer-the-importance-of-recognizing-juneteenth-and-diversity-in|title=Black voices in soccer: The importance of recognizing Juneteenth and diversity in the game|work=[[MLS Next Pro]]}}</ref><ref name=Canada>{{Canada Soccer player|id=56841}}</ref> He played youth soccer with Erin Mills SC and GPS Academy <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CRGwwW2UElQ|title=Who is Canada's newest striker option? 1-on-1 with Tani Oluwaseyi - VAMOS! Presented by Degree|date=July 8, 2024|work=[[OneSoccer]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/tani-oluwaseyi-seizes-moment-with-minnesota-united-i-ve-been-waiting|title=Tani Oluwaseyi seizes moment with Minnesota United: "I've been waiting"|first=Charles|last=Boehm|date=April 26, 2024|work=[[Major League Soccer]]}}</ref>

He attended [[St. Joan of Arc Catholic Secondary School]]. At St. Joan of Arc, he captained the Angels to a 17–0 record and a Provincial High School Championship as a senior he scored 30 goals and tallied ten assists while serving as a team captain. He was also a three-time MVP of the boys soccer team, scoring a total of 68 times over a four-year career. While at high school, Oluwaseyi also played club soccer for the GPS Academy, where he won the Golden Boot Award at the 2017 [[SuperCupNI]], at which his team won the Vase Cup. He also led his team to Ontario Academy Soccer League and Provincial Indoor Soccer League Championships.<ref name="auto">{{Cite web|url=https://redstormsports.com/sports/mens-soccer/roster/tani-oluwaseyi/4427|title=Tani Oluwaseyi - Men's Soccer|website=St. John's University Athletics}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.torchonline.com/sports/2019/10/16/tani-oluwaseyi-has-found-his-confidence-in-2019/|title=Tani Oluwaseyi Has Found His Confidence In 2019|first=Brendan|last=Murray}}</ref>

==College career==
In 2018, Oluwaseyi committed to playing [[College soccer in the United States|college soccer]] at [[St. John's University (New York City)|St. John's University]]. In a four year college career, Oluwaseyi went on to make 49 appearances, scoring 20 goals and tallying ten assists.<ref name="auto"/> He missed nearly all his entire senior season,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stormthepaint.com/2021/07/26/st-johns-soccer-tani-oluwaseyi-injured/|title=St. John's soccer star Tani Oluwaseyi will miss entire 2021 season|date=July 26, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bvmsports.com/2021/12/02/red-storm-soccer-miss-impact-left-by-tani-oluwaseyi/|title=Red Storm soccer miss impact left by Tani Oluwaseyi|date=December 2, 2021|website=BVM Sports}}</ref> and his sophomore season was truncated by the [[COVID-19 pandemic]]. However, he earned numerous college accolades, including BIG EAST All-Freshman Team selection in 2018, BIG EAST Offensive Player of the Year, First Team All-BIG EAST, and United Soccer Coaches First Team All-Atlantic Region in 2019, and First Team All-BIG EAST, and United Soccer Coaches All-East Region Second Team in the 2020–21 season.<ref name="auto"/>

==Club career==
===Semi-professional===
In 2021, Oluwaseyi appeared for local side [[Manhattan SC]] in the [[USL League Two]], where he scored a single goal during his two appearances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uslleaguetwo.com/roster_players/46771307|title=Manhattan SC &#124; uslleaguetwo.com|website=www.uslleaguetwo.com}}</ref> He also played with [[New York Pancyprian-Freedoms]], who compete in the fifth-tier [[Eastern Premier Soccer League|EPSL]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eleftheriapancyprian.com/news/former-nypf-players-oluwaseyi-and-simonsen-picked-in-2022-mls-super-draft|title=Former NYPF Players Oluwaseyi and Simonsen Picked in 2022 MLS SUPER DRAFT|website=Eleftheria Pancyprian Soccer Club}}</ref> He was also named on the roster for [[National Premier Soccer League|NPSL]] side [[FC Golden State]], but didn't make an appearance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://npsl.bonzidev.com/sam/standings/ss/schedule.php?containerID=MTUxMTI0NTY=&v=3|title=National Premier Soccer League|website=npsl.bonzidev.com|access-date=August 20, 2022|archive-date=October 22, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211022124531/http://npsl.bonzidev.com/sam/standings/ss/schedule.php?v=3&containerID=MTUxMTI0NTY=|url-status=dead}}</ref>

===Minnesota United===

In January 2022, it was announced Oluwaseyi would be available in the [[2022 MLS SuperDraft]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://northerntribune.ca/2022-mls-superdraft-canadians/|title=Who Are The Canadians In The MLS SuperDraft?|date=January 9, 2022}}</ref>
<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thestar.com/sports/soccer/mls/2022/01/09/red-storm-have-a-bit-of-everything-available-in-tuesdays-mls-superdraft.html|title=red storm have a bit of everything available in tuesdays|website=[[Toronto Star]] |date=January 9, 2022}}</ref> On January 11, he was selected 17th overall by [[Minnesota United FC|Minnesota United]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mnufc.com/news/mnufc-select-forward-tani-oluwaseyi-in-the-2022-mls-superdraft|title=MNUFC Select Forward Tani Oluwaseyi in the 2022 MLS Superdraft &#124; Minnesota United FC|website=MNUFC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.torchonline.com/sports/2022/01/30/red-stormin-the-mls-three-johnnies-selected-in-superdraft/|title=Red Stormin' the MLS: Three Johnnies Selected In SuperDraft|first=Sara|last=Kiernan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Trio of Canadians taken in opening round of MLS SuperDraft {{!}} CBC Sports |date=January 12, 2022 |website=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230203212806/https://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/mls/mls-three-canadians-taken-first-round-superdraft-1.6311601 |archive-date=February 3, 2023 |url-status=live |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/mls/mls-three-canadians-taken-first-round-superdraft-1.6311601}}</ref> On February 25, Oluwaseyi signed a one-year deal with Minnesota.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mnufc.com/news/mnufc-signs-mls-superdraft-pick-forward-tani-oluwaseyi|title=MNUFC Signs MLS SuperDraft Pick Forward Tani Oluwaseyi &#124; Minnesota United FC|website=MNUFC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/minnesota-united-fc-sign-forward-tani-oluwaseyi|title=Minnesota United FC sign forward Tani Oluwaseyi &#124; MLSSoccer.com|website=mlssoccer}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.startribune.com/meet-the-new-minnesota-united-players-mls-loons-2022/600150678/|title=Meet the new Minnesota United players for 2022|first=Jerry Zgoda Star|last=Tribune|website=Star Tribune|date=February 26, 2022 }}</ref> During the 2022 season, he spent time with [[Minnesota United FC 2|Minnesota United 2]] in [[MLS Next Pro]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlsnextpro.com/players/tanitoluwa-oluwaseyi/|title=Tanitoluwa Oluwaseyi &#124; MLSsoccer.com|website=mlsnextpro}}</ref> In November 2022 Minnesota announced they had exercised Oluwaseyi's contract option, keeping him at the club through 2023.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mnufc.com/news/minnesota-united-2022-end-of-season-roster-update|title=Minnesota United 2022 End of Season Roster Update|date=December 21, 2022}}</ref>

In April 2023, he was loaned to [[USL Championship]] side [[San Antonio FC]] for the remainder of the [[2023 USL Championship season|2023 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mnufc.com/news/minnesota-united-loans-forward-tani-oluwaseyi-to-san-antonio-fc|date=April 27, 2023|title=Minnesota United Loans Forward Tani Oluwaseyi to San Antonio FC|work=[[Minnesota United FC|Minnesota United]]}}</ref> In his debut for San Antonio on May 7, Oluwaseyi scored the game-winning goal in a 2-1 victory over the [[Las Vegas Lights FC|Las Vegas Lights]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ksat.com/video/sports/2023/05/08/oluwaseyis-goal-lifts-san-antonio-fc-to-2-1-road-victory-over-las-vegas-lights-fc/|work=[[KSAT-TV|KSAT]]|date=May 7, 2023|title=Oluwaseyi's goal lifts San Antonio FC to 2-1 road victory over Las Vegas Lights FC}}</ref>  On May 14, he scored a hat-trick against the [[Charleston Battery]] in a 7-0 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ksat.com/video/sports/2023/05/15/oluwaseyi-tallies-hat-trick-in-san-antonio-fcs-breakthrough-performance-against-charleston-battery/|date=May 14, 2023|title=Oluwaseyi tallies hat trick in San Antonio FC's breakthrough performance against Charleston Battery|work=[[KSAT-TV|KSAT]]}}</ref> On July 7, Oluwaseyi got his second hat-trick against [[Memphis 901 FC|Memphis 901]] in a 4-0 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sanantoniofc.com/news/2023/07/07/safc-shuts-out-memphis-901-fc-4-0-on-the-road/|date=July 7, 2023|title=SAFC SHUTS OUT MEMPHIS 901 FC 4-0 ON THE ROAD|work=[[San Antonio FC]]}}</ref> Three weeks later on July 29, he would score four goals against [[Hartford Athletic]] in a 5-2 win, reaching 13 goals on the season and breaking San Antonio's single season scoring record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sanantoniofc.com/news/2023/07/30/san-antonio-fc-beats-hartford-athletic-5-2-behind-four-goals-from-tani-oluwaseyi/|date=July 29, 2023|title=SAN ANTONIO FC BEATS HARTFORD ATHLETIC 5-2 BEHIND FOUR GOALS FROM TANI OLUWASEYI|work=[[San Antonio FC]]}}</ref>

On March 2, 2024, Oluwaseyi scored his first MLS goal, a stoppage-time equalizer as Minnesota United drew the [[Columbus Crew]] 1-1. After scoring 8 goals and 6 assists in the 2024 season, Oluwaseyi would be signed to a contract extension through the 2027 season, with a club option for 2028.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mnufc.com/news/minnesota-united-signs-forward-tani-oluwaseyi-to-contract-extension|title=Minnesota United Signs Forward Tani Oluwaseyi to Contract Extension|website=Minnesota United|date=December 3, 2024}}</ref>

===Villarreal===
On August 29, 2025, Spanish side [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] announced they had acquired Oluwaseyi from Minnesota, with the forward signing a deal until 2030.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://villarrealcf.es/en/tani-oluwaseyi-joins-villarreal-cf/|date=August 29, 2025|title=Tani Oluwaseyi joins Villarreal CF}}</ref> He made his debut for the club on August 31, coming on as a substitute against [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]] in an eventual 1-1 draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://villarrealcf.es/en/match-report-late-blow-denies-villarreal-victory-at-balaidos-villarreal-celta-md3-laliga/|date=August 31, 2025|title=Late blow denies Villarreal victory at Balaídos (1-1)}}</ref> He scored his first [[La Liga]] goal for Villareal on September 23, 2025 against [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]], three days after earning his first assist for the club.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Villarreal 2-1 Sevilla (24 Sep, 2025) Final Score - ESPN (AU) |url=https://www.espn.com.au/football/match/_/gameId/748196/villarreal-sevilla |access-date=2025-09-23 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Villarreal 2-1 Osasuna (Sep 20, 2025) Final Score |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/748189/osasuna-villarreal |access-date=2025-09-23 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref>

==International career==
Oluwaseyi was born in Nigeria, but having lived in Canada from age 10, Oluwaseyi was eligible to represent both the [[Nigeria national football team|Nigerian national team]] and the [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canadian national team]].

In June 2024, he was announced as a late addition to the Canada squad ahead of two friendlies against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] and [[France national football team|France]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/canada-add-minnesota-united-s-tani-oluwaseyi-for-june-friendlies|date=June 3, 2024|title=Canada add Minnesota United's Tani Oluwaseyi for June friendlies|work=[[Major League Soccer]]}}</ref> He made his debut against the latter on June 9 at the [[Nouveau Stade de Bordeaux|Matmut Atlantique]]. He substituted [[Ismaël Koné]] in the 84th minute as the game ended in a goalless draw.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=ESPN|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/701986/|title=France v Canada game report|date=June 9, 2024}}</ref> On June 15, 2024, Oluwaseyi was named to Canada's squad for the [[2024 Copa América]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canadasoccer.com/news/canmnt-announce-2024-copa-america-roster/|title=CANMNT ANNOUNCE 2024 COPA AMÉRICA ROSTER|date=June 15, 2024|work= [[Canadian Soccer Association]]}}</ref> He became cap-tied to Canada in a 1–0 win against Peru on June 25, 2024, substituting for [[Cyle Larin]] in the 82nd minute.<ref>{{cite web |title=Copa America Match Details - Canada vs Peru |url=https://www.concacaf.com/en/copa-america/game-details?matchid=726968 |website=Concacaf | date=May 2, 2024 |access-date=June 26, 2024}}</ref> On March 23, 2025, Oluwaseyi scored his debut goal, the first in a 2–1 win against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] in the [[2025 CONCACAF Nations League Finals]] third place match.

